Package myAdapter

Class MapAdapter.EntrySet

  • java.lang.Object
    • myAdapter.MapAdapter.EntrySet
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    HCollection, HSet
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    MapAdapter.KeySet, MapAdapter.ValueSet
    Enclosing class:
    MapAdapter
    private class MapAdapter.EntrySet
extends java.lang.Object
implements HSet

    A HSet which contains all the entries of a MapAdapter, elements of type Entry

    Used for the method HMap.entrySet(), especially to guarantee the requested backing

    It uses its relative MapAdapter as the unique istance variable

      • add

        public boolean add​(java.lang.Object o)
        Description copied from interface: HSet

        Adds the specified element to this set if it is not already present (optional operation). More formally, adds the specified element, o, to this set if this set contains no element e such that (o==null ? e==null : o.equals(e)). If this set already contains the specified element, the call leaves this set unchanged and returns false. In combination with the restriction on constructors, this ensures that sets never contain duplicate elements.

        The stipulation above does not imply that sets must accept all elements; sets may refuse to add any particular element, including null, and throwing an exception, as described in the specification for Collection.add. Individual set implementations should clearly document any restrictions on the the elements that they may contain.

        Specified by:
        add in interface HCollection
        Specified by:
        add in interface HSet
        Parameters:
        o - element to be added to this set.
        Returns:
        true if this set did not already contain the specified element.
        Throws:
        myLib.UnsupportedOperationException - for safety reasons, the add operation on an EntrySet is not allowed

      • equals

        public boolean equals​(java.lang.Object o)
        Compares the specified object with this EntrySet for equality. Returns true if and only if the specified object is also a EntrySet, both EntrySet have the same size, and all corresponding pairs of elements in the two EntrySet are equal. (Two elements e1 and e2 are equal if (e1==null ? e2==null : e1.equals(e2)).) In other words, two EntrySets are defined to be equal if they contain the same elements in the same order.

      • hashCode

        public int hashCode()
        Returns the hash code value for this EntrySet. The hash code of an EntrySet is defined to be the result of the following calculation: hashCode = 1; Iterator i = EntrySet.iterator(); while (i.hasNext()) { Entry e = (Entry)iter.next(); hashCode += e.getKey().hashCode() + e.getValue().hashCode(); } This ensures that EntrySet1.equals(EntrySet2) implies that EntrySet1.hashCode()==EntrySet2.hashCode() for any two lists, EntrySet1 and EntrySet2, as required by the general contract of hashCode()
